The paper deals with the problem of computing an $\epsilon$-hull, which is a fundamental problem in computational geometry and approximation algorithms. This suggests that cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is a likely sub-category. The problem is also related to data streams, which suggests that cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is another likely sub-category. The paper proposes algorithms that use minimal space, which is a common theme in machine learning and data mining, suggesting that cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.DM (Data Mining) are also possible sub-categories. Finally, the paper deals with the structure of data and how it can be used to improve algorithms, which suggests that cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is a possible sub-category as well.
